{{refimprove|date=March 2016}}'''Semasiography''' (from {{lang-el|σημασία}} (semasia) "signification, meaning" and {{lang-el|γραφία}} (graphia) "writing") is "writing with signs", a non-phonetic based technique to "communicate information without the necessary intercession of forms of speech." It means written symbols and languages that are not based on spoken words. It predated the advent of the creation of the language-based writing system<ref>{{Cite book|last=Powell |first=Barry B. |author-link=Barry B. Powell |title=Writing: Theory and History of the Technology of Civilization|year=2012|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |isbn=978-1-118-25532-2}}</ref> and is used contemporarily in [[computer icon]]s, [[musical notation]], [[emoji]] and [[mathematical notation]]. It is studied in [[semasiology]] within the field of [[linguistics]].
